1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,780
There are some common issues that make data messy or untidy.

2
00:00:03,780 --> 00:00:05,790
Let's recap these. One,

3
00:00:05,790 --> 00:00:08,640
column headers being values rather than variable names.

4
00:00:08,640 --> 00:00:11,850
Two, multiple variables being stored in one column.

5
00:00:11,850 --> 00:00:15,660
Three, variables being stored in both rows and columns.

6
00:00:15,660 --> 00:00:19,890
Four, multiple types of observational units being stored in the same table,

7
00:00:19,890 --> 00:00:24,465
and five, a single observational unit being stored in multiple tables.

8
00:00:24,465 --> 00:00:25,950
To solve these issues,

9
00:00:25,950 --> 00:00:28,485
we need to know some data structuring and techniques.

10
00:00:28,485 --> 00:00:32,940
Column headers are values not variable names is a common data structure issue.

11
00:00:32,940 --> 00:00:34,365
Let's briefly visit it.

12
00:00:34,365 --> 00:00:36,350
In the dataset on the top we can see

13
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:39,560
how different ranges of test scores are part of the header.

14
00:00:39,560 --> 00:00:43,730
These should ideally be placed in a single column as values.

15
00:00:43,730 --> 00:00:47,450
What do we do? We can use a function called unpivoting,

16
00:00:47,450 --> 00:00:48,620
also known as melting,

17
00:00:48,620 --> 00:00:51,860
to transform data across columns into a single column.

18
00:00:51,860 --> 00:00:54,185
See the bottom table after unpivoting,

19
00:00:54,185 --> 00:00:57,500
we can now see that the different ranges are now stored in

20
00:00:57,500 --> 00:01:01,300
one column and the frequency values are also in a single column.

21
00:01:01,300 --> 00:01:05,540
Unpivoting is really useful when you need to convert a wide dataset with

22
00:01:05,540 --> 00:01:09,950
many columns into a long format with fewer columns and more rows.

23
00:01:09,950 --> 00:01:12,650
This transformation is helpful for certain types of

24
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:15,475
data analysis that required data in long format.

25
00:01:15,475 --> 00:01:18,135
What if we'd like to do the opposite?

26
00:01:18,135 --> 00:01:20,590
Pivoting is the opposite of unpivoting and is

27
00:01:20,590 --> 00:01:24,685
a very popular method for being able to get a clearer understanding of data.

28
00:01:24,685 --> 00:01:26,765
Let's take a look at how and why.

29
00:01:26,765 --> 00:01:30,715
Here we have an example dataset of hypothetical products and revenue.

30
00:01:30,715 --> 00:01:33,040
Our simple dataset has four columns.

31
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:37,615
Product classification, whether the product is an early prototype pilot work product,

32
00:01:37,615 --> 00:01:42,730
the products A, B, and C. The year when the product is built and the revenue in dollars.

33
00:01:42,730 --> 00:01:45,670
Notice how it's challenging to get an idea of the revenue for

34
00:01:45,670 --> 00:01:49,655
the three products over the years since the rows are intermixed.

35
00:01:49,655 --> 00:01:52,630
We can use a function called pivoting to convert

36
00:01:52,630 --> 00:01:56,695
a long dataset into a wide dataset and create useful groupings.

37
00:01:56,695 --> 00:02:00,935
For example here we can now clearly see that products A and C

38
00:02:00,935 --> 00:02:05,495
were an early prototype stage in 2021 and made it $0 in revenue.

39
00:02:05,495 --> 00:02:11,140
The early prototype version of these two products were not continued into 2022 and 2023.

40
00:02:11,140 --> 00:02:14,220
Now, Products A and B were both pilots.

41
00:02:14,220 --> 00:02:18,665
Product B made $3,885 in revenue in 2021,

42
00:02:18,665 --> 00:02:22,160
whereas Product A made $2,193 in revenue in

43
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:27,710
2022 because it was still an early prototype stage in 2021, and so on.

44
00:02:27,710 --> 00:02:30,315
When you use unpivoting versus pivoting,

45
00:02:30,315 --> 00:02:35,420
use unpivoting to turn a dataset into a standard format for performing analyses.

46
00:02:35,420 --> 00:02:40,145
Use pivoting to turn data tables into easier to understand representations of the data,

47
00:02:40,145 --> 00:02:42,070
for example for presentations.

48
00:02:42,070 --> 00:02:46,165
Transposing is another popular operation that's used for data structuring.

49
00:02:46,165 --> 00:02:48,410
Take a look at the example on the screen where we

50
00:02:48,410 --> 00:02:50,645
have student IDs that are part of the header.

51
00:02:50,645 --> 00:02:52,505
The first row is the student's names.

52
00:02:52,505 --> 00:02:54,805
In the second row is the student's test score.

53
00:02:54,805 --> 00:02:57,320
We see the common issue of column headers being

54
00:02:57,320 --> 00:02:59,870
values not variable names in this DataFrame,

55
00:02:59,870 --> 00:03:01,550
it can be challenging to access

56
00:03:01,550 --> 00:03:04,700
a specific students test score when the DataFrame is in this format.

57
00:03:04,700 --> 00:03:09,145
It's overall a somewhat challenging format for manipulating and navigating the data.

58
00:03:09,145 --> 00:03:12,170
We can transpose this into the DataFrame on the bottom,

59
00:03:12,170 --> 00:03:14,420
which has neat columns for each variable,

60
00:03:14,420 --> 00:03:15,770
for example the ID,

61
00:03:15,770 --> 00:03:17,210
the students, and the test score.

62
00:03:17,210 --> 00:03:19,745
We can also transpose the DataFrame on the bottom,

63
00:03:19,745 --> 00:03:21,365
back into the DataFrame on the top,

64
00:03:21,365 --> 00:03:23,890
if we would like to follow that format instead.

65
00:03:23,890 --> 00:03:27,065
Data merging is another technique for data structuring.

66
00:03:27,065 --> 00:03:30,940
Consider the two separate data tables on the screen that were stored separately,

67
00:03:30,940 --> 00:03:33,230
do separate data collection and poor planning.

68
00:03:33,230 --> 00:03:36,335
The DataTable on the left contains the ID of the movie,

69
00:03:36,335 --> 00:03:39,425
and movie title, and the viewers as part of her viewers dataset.

70
00:03:39,425 --> 00:03:42,635
Similarly, the table on the right contains the ID of the movie,

71
00:03:42,635 --> 00:03:45,335
a review, and an associated rating.

72
00:03:45,335 --> 00:03:47,270
Here we're seeing the common issue of

73
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:50,320
a single observational unit being stored in multiple tables.

74
00:03:50,320 --> 00:03:54,380
Since the two tables have the same observational unit of an individual movie,

75
00:03:54,380 --> 00:03:58,185
they should ideally be one table with the same observational unit.

76
00:03:58,185 --> 00:04:01,850
We can merge these two tables side-by-side using

77
00:04:01,850 --> 00:04:06,970
the ID column as our key to get one table with all of the required information.

78
00:04:06,970 --> 00:04:09,230
This is a straightforward example of merge,

79
00:04:09,230 --> 00:04:12,100
although there can be various types of merges.

80
00:04:12,100 --> 00:04:14,885
Data appending, also known as concatenating,

81
00:04:14,885 --> 00:04:17,000
is a similar technique today merging.

82
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:19,565
While merging is joining two tables together

83
00:04:19,565 --> 00:04:22,340
side-by-side by a unique key to align the data.

84
00:04:22,340 --> 00:04:24,560
Appending means taking two tables with

85
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:28,600
the same variables and adding the data points from one table to another table.

86
00:04:28,600 --> 00:04:30,845
For example take a look at the table on top.

87
00:04:30,845 --> 00:04:34,970
If I wanted to append the second table to it as part of a simple append operation,

88
00:04:34,970 --> 00:04:38,755
I could just add the rows from the second table to the end of the top table.

89
00:04:38,755 --> 00:04:44,270
Group-bys and aggregations are handy Pandas functions to get a summary table of the data.

90
00:04:44,270 --> 00:04:47,630
Group-by allows you to group categorical data together,

91
00:04:47,630 --> 00:04:50,210
and aggregating the values associated with them can be

92
00:04:50,210 --> 00:04:53,305
done using aggregate functions like a sell more amine.

93
00:04:53,305 --> 00:04:55,490
Let's take a look at an example of this.

94
00:04:55,490 --> 00:05:00,515
On the left, I have a simple dataset with a date column listing months, and score column.

95
00:05:00,515 --> 00:05:04,310
If I were to perform a Group-by on this DataFrame to get the sum

96
00:05:04,310 --> 00:05:08,360
of the score and the mean of the score for each month.

97
